7. Queries using Aggregate functions, GROUP BY, HAVING and Creation and dropping of Views


Aggregate Functions, GROUP BY, HAVING & Views
1. Aim

To perform SQL queries using aggregate functions, GROUP BY, HAVING, and to create and drop views.

2. Theory
Aggregate Functions → Perform calculations on multiple rows (COUNT, SUM, AVG, MAX, MIN)
GROUP BY → Groups rows for aggregation
HAVING → Filters grouped data
View → A virtual table created from a query
3. Program / Procedure
Step 1: Create Table
CREATE TABLE Student (
    RollNo INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(30),
    Dept VARCHAR(10),
    Marks INT
);
Step 2: Insert Data
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (101, 'Ravi', 'CSE', 85);
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (102, 'Anu', 'ECE', 78);
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (103, 'Kiran', 'CSE', 92);
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (104, 'Sita', 'ECE', 88);
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (105, 'Ram', 'EEE', 70);
4. Queries
a) Aggregate Functions
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Student;
SELECT AVG(Marks) FROM Student;
SELECT MAX(Marks) FROM Student;
SELECT MIN(Marks) FROM Student;
b) GROUP BY

Department-wise average marks

SELECT Dept, AVG(Marks) AS AvgMarks
FROM Student
GROUP BY Dept;
c) HAVING

Departments with average marks > 80

SELECT Dept, AVG(Marks) AS AvgMarks
FROM Student
GROUP BY Dept
HAVING AVG(Marks) > 80;
d) CREATE VIEW
CREATE VIEW Top_Students AS
SELECT RollNo, Name, Marks
FROM Student
WHERE Marks > 80;
e) Display View
SELECT * FROM Top_Students;
f) DROP VIEW
DROP VIEW Top_Students;
5. Output (What to Write)
Aggregate functions calculated successfully
GROUP BY grouped data correctly
HAVING filtered grouped results
View created, displayed, and dropped successfully
